===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{m|enm|tool}}, from {{etyl|ang|en}} {{m|ang|tōl||tool, implement, instrument|lit=that with which one prepares something}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{m|gem-pro|*tōlą||tool}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{m|ine-pro|*dewh₂-||to tie to, secure}}, equivalent to {{suffix|taw|t1=to prepare|le|lang=en}} {{gloss|agent suffix}}. Cognate with {{cog|sco|tuil||tool, implement, instrument, device}}, {{cog|is|tól||tool}}, {{cog|fo|tól||tool, instrument}}. Related to {{cog|ang|tāwian||to make, prepare, or cultivate}}; see {{l|en|taw}}, and {{l|en|tow}} ("fibres used for spinning").<ref>{{cite-book|last=Carus|first=Paul|title=The philosophy of the tool|publisher=The Open Court Publishing Company|pages=3-4|location=Chicago|date=1893|ref=refCarus1893}}</ref><ref>{{cite-book|last=Hall|first=John Richard Clark|others=Supplement by Herbert D. Merritt|title=A Concise Anglo-Saxon Dictionary|publisher=Cambridge University Press|pages=338 & 345|year=1960|year_published=1984|edition=4|isbn=9780802065483|ref=refHall1984}}</ref>

